      <h2>Why Pilot.BM exists</h2>
      <p>
        Every Bermuda guide we found was either a tourism board brochure or a budget-backpacker blog.
        Neither one answered the questions we actually had: How do you actually get around without a car?
        What salary do you need to cover Bermuda's cost of living? What's the one-car-per-household rule
        and why does it matter if you're moving in with a partner?
      </p>
      <p>
        The tourism boards write for people who've already decided to visit and want to be reassured.
        The backpacker blogs write for people who want the cheapest possible experience.
        Neither speaks to the discerning visitor who wants real information, or the professional
        who is considering moving to Bermuda and needs to understand what they're getting into.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Pilot.BM fills that gap.</strong>
      </p>

      <h2>Who built this</h2>
      <p>
        My name is <strong>Matt Corbett</strong>. I'm a US-based financial analyst with regulatory expertise
        and connections to Bermuda's international business sector. Bermuda's economy is built on
        insurance, reinsurance, and fund administration — the kind of regulated financial infrastructure
        I work with professionally.
      </p>
      <p>
        That background means I understand why the immigration rules are the way they are, why the health
        insurance mandate matters, why the Assessment Number system exists, and how to read the government
        sources accurately. It also means I know when information is stale or oversimplified.
      </p>
      <p>
        Contact: <a href="mailto:matt@ravenpower.net">matt@ravenpower.net</a>
      </p>

      <h2>How Pilot.BM works</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>We research and cite sources.</strong> Every regulated figure (health insurance rates,
          permit fees, duty rates) includes a source and a verification date. We note when something
          is unverified.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We flag what's changed.</strong> The Work From Bermuda programme closed on 28 February 2025.
          We updated on the day it closed. We don't leave stale information up because it's inconvenient to update.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We mark uncertainty clearly.</strong> Where data is synthesis rather than a citable primary
          source, we say so: <em>[unverified — verify at gov.bm]</em>. We never present uncertain figures
          as fact.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>We don't write for search volume alone.</strong> Pilot.BM is not a content farm.
          Every page serves a genuine user need. We build fewer, better pages.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Affiliate disclosure</h2>
      <p>
        Pilot.BM uses affiliate links on some pages. When you click a link marked with a "sponsored" rel
        attribute and make a purchase, we may earn a commission at no additional cost to you.
      </p>
      <p>
        Affiliate relationships do not influence editorial coverage. Businesses are listed in the directory
        based on quality and relevance, not on whether they have a commercial relationship with us.
        Paid listings (Standard/Featured/Anchor) are clearly labelled with their tier badge.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="/Pilot.BM/legal/affiliate-disclosure">Full affiliate disclosure →</a>
      </p>

      <h2>Our editorial standard</h2>
      <p>
        Bermuda has enough bad information. The visa programme that closed years ago still shows as
        "available" on sites that haven't been updated. The transport rules that matter most (no rental
        cars) are buried or missing entirely. The cost of living figures that circulate online are
        often outdated or cherry-picked.
      </p>
      <p>
        We hold ourselves to a simple standard: <strong>write what's true, cite where it's from,
        update when things change, and say so clearly when we don't know.</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        If you find something that's wrong or out of date, email us.
        <a href="mailto:matt@ravenpower.net">matt@ravenpower.net</a>
      </p>

